Cookie:<br><br>
Mark Twain said something to the effect..There are lies..damn lies and then there are statistics.<br><br>
I, for one, have an appreciation for empirical truth.  The methodology is more important than the findings.  <br>
If the method is off then the findings are fiction.<br><br>
I don't find what is reported above to be dangerous or threating to me as a Vietnam Veteran.  Suffice it to say that regardless of the numbers.. the problem is there and it is a big one.<br><br>
Out of all the causation and contributing variables that lead to dysfunctioning after trauma.. we are left with a puzzle.  Why are some more affected than others?<br><br>
One thing that troubles me is that some veterans look down on their brothers with distain because he is having problems and they are not.  The Veterans Administration is loaded with vets who poo poo away PTSD.  They strut in front of the secretaries saying, &quot;Hell, I was over there.. it didn't bother me!&quot;  What they fail to convey is the fact that they worked at some NCO Club or had a non-threating job.<br><br>
Admiration for my fellow veterans that continue to function at a high level is a luxuary... Concern for those who are not functioning so well is a great drain on my resources.<br><br>
MTF<br>

